vermeer@panix.com (David C) writes:

>	This question comes to mind after reading this thread. I understand
>from a fella using NT that NT is written in MACH... where did MACH come from,
>and what makes it not *NIX? MACH seems pretty neat, small... slippery...
>if NT is based on it, will there be like a "Visual MACH" so we can write in
>it too? I mean, how can such a fabulous OS come outta nowhere? (Oh yea, I
>forgot... in Latin "nowhere" is "utopia"... )... and what's this about sched-
>ualing "jobs" (or what ever Bill wants to call them... )?    ? (really...)


At one time some confused people at Microsoft said that Windows NT had
a Microkernel, since that was the hottest new OS buzzword at the time.
For some reasons some journalists (the only people stupid enough
that I can think of, off hand) then decided that NT was obviously
based on MACH, then the best known microkernel.  (While MACH at that
point wasn't really a microkernel, it was intended to be a microkernle
in its next inception: MACH 3.0)

Windows NT is not built on top of MACH (which is what you mean by
"written in", I suppose), nor can it be considered a Microkernel
by any standard.

Casper

