In article <35eaek$e89@panix3.panix.com>, vermeer@panix.com (David C) wrote:
> 	This question comes to mind after reading this thread. I understand
> from a fella using NT that NT is written in MACH...

Mach is a set of three operating system kernels that went from
monolithic to fully microkernel.  NT isn't connected to any of them,
except in the minds of foolish people who assume that anything labeled
"microkernel" is necessarily based on Mach.

WPOS/Workplace/OS2-PPC's microkernel is based on the Mach 3.0
microkernel.

> where did MACH come from,
> and what makes it not *NIX?

Lineage.

> MACH seems pretty neat, small... slippery...
> if NT is based on it, will there be like a "Visual MACH" so we can write in
> it too? I mean, how can such a fabulous OS come outta nowhere?

Mach is not a language.  NT was written in C and C++.

